# Port Slack Computation to Rust WASM

## Context
Slack measures how much an issue can be delayed without affecting the critical path. Zero slack = on critical path.

## Go Implementation Reference
```go
// computeSlack in graph.go
// Longest-path slack: 0 on critical path
```

## Rust Implementation (slack.rs)
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;
use crate::algorithms::topo::topological_sort;

/// Compute slack for each node.
/// Slack = (longest path through graph) - (longest path through this node)
pub fn slack(graph: &DiGraph) -> Vec<f64> {
    let n = graph.node_count();
    if n == 0 {
        return Vec::new();
    }

    let order = match topological_sort(graph) {
        Some(o) => o,
        None => return vec![0.0; n],
    };

    // Forward pass: longest distance from any start
    let mut dist_from_start = vec![0; n];
    for &v in &order {
        for &u in graph.predecessors(v) {
            dist_from_start[v] = dist_from_start[v].max(dist_from_start[u] + 1);
        }
    }

    // Backward pass: longest distance to any end
    let mut dist_to_end = vec![0; n];
    for &v in order.iter().rev() {
        for &w in graph.successors(v) {
            dist_to_end[v] = dist_to_end[v].max(dist_to_end[w] + 1);
        }
    }

    // Longest path in graph
    let longest = (0..n)
        .map(|i| dist_from_start[i] + dist_to_end[i])
        .max()
        .unwrap_or(0);

    // Slack = longest - (dist_from_start + dist_to_end)
    (0..n)
        .map(|i| (longest - dist_from_start[i] - dist_to_end[i]) as f64)
        .collect()
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Nodes on critical path have slack 0
- [ ] Slack values non-negative
- [ ] Results match Go implementation

# Port K-Shortest Paths and Parallel Cut

## Context
K-Shortest Paths finds multiple critical paths through the graph. Parallel Cut analyzes opportunities for parallel work.

## Go Implementation Reference
```go
// KPathsResult, ParallelCutResult in advanced_insights.go
```

## Rust Implementation

### advanced/k_paths.rs
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;
use crate::algorithms::topo::topological_sort;

pub struct CriticalPath {
    pub nodes: Vec<usize>,
    pub length: usize,
}

/// Find k longest paths in DAG.
pub fn k_critical_paths(graph: &DiGraph, k: usize) -> Vec<CriticalPath> {
    let n = graph.node_count();
    if n == 0 { return Vec::new(); }

    let order = match topological_sort(graph) {
        Some(o) => o,
        None => return Vec::new(),
    };

    // Compute distances and track predecessors
    let mut dist = vec![0usize; n];
    let mut pred = vec![None; n];

    for &v in &order {
        for &u in graph.predecessors(v) {
            if dist[u] + 1 > dist[v] {
                dist[v] = dist[u] + 1;
                pred[v] = Some(u);
            }
        }
    }

    // Find k sinks with longest paths
    let mut sinks: Vec<(usize, usize)> = (0..n)
        .filter(|&v| graph.out_degree(v) == 0 || dist[v] > 0)
        .map(|v| (v, dist[v]))
        .collect();
    sinks.sort_by(|a, b| b.1.cmp(&a.1));
    sinks.truncate(k);

    // Reconstruct paths
    sinks.iter().map(|&(sink, len)| {
        let mut path = vec![sink];
        let mut curr = sink;
        while let Some(p) = pred[curr] {
            path.push(p);
            curr = p;
        }
        path.reverse();
        CriticalPath { nodes: path, length: len + 1 }
    }).collect()
}
```

### advanced/parallel_cut.rs
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;

pub struct ParallelCutItem {
    pub node: usize,
    pub parallel_gain: i32,
}

/// Find issues that increase parallelization when completed.
pub fn parallel_cut_suggestions(graph: &DiGraph, closed_set: &[bool], limit: usize) -> Vec<ParallelCutItem> {
    let n = graph.node_count();
    let mut suggestions: Vec<ParallelCutItem> = (0..n)
        .filter(|&v| !closed_set.get(v).copied().unwrap_or(false))
        .map(|v| {
            // Count how many dependents become actionable
            let gain = graph.successors(v).iter()
                .filter(|&&w| {
                    !closed_set.get(w).copied().unwrap_or(false) &&
                    graph.predecessors(w).iter()
                        .filter(|&&p| p != v)
                        .all(|&p| closed_set.get(p).copied().unwrap_or(false))
                })
                .count();
            ParallelCutItem { node: v, parallel_gain: gain as i32 - 1 }
        })
        .filter(|item| item.parallel_gain > 0)
        .collect();

    suggestions.sort_by(|a, b| b.parallel_gain.cmp(&a.parallel_gain));
    suggestions.truncate(limit);
    suggestions
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] K paths returned in length order
- [ ] Parallel cut identifies bottleneck removals
- [ ] Results match Go advanced_insights

# Implement Hash-Based Routing for SPA Navigation

## Context
The static viewer needs client-side routing to navigate between views (dashboard, issues list, issue detail, insights) without page reloads. Hash-based routing works perfectly for static hosting.

## Requirements

### URL Structure
```
#/                      â†’ Dashboard
#/issues                â†’ Issues list
#/issues?status=open    â†’ Filtered issues list
#/issue/bv-123          â†’ Issue detail
#/insights              â†’ Insights view
```

### Router Implementation
```javascript
// viewer.js

const routes = {
    '/': 'dashboard',
    '/issues': 'issues',
    '/issue/:id': 'issue',
    '/insights': 'insights'
};

function initRouter() {
    // Parse current hash and navigate
    window.addEventListener('hashchange', handleRoute);
    handleRoute(); // Handle initial route
}

function handleRoute() {
    const hash = window.location.hash.slice(1) || '/';
    const [path, query] = hash.split('?');

    // Parse query params
    const params = new URLSearchParams(query);

    // Match route
    for (const [pattern, view] of Object.entries(routes)) {
        const match = matchRoute(pattern, path);
        if (match) {
            navigateTo(view, match.params, params);
            return;
        }
    }

    // Default to dashboard
    navigateTo('dashboard', {}, params);
}

function matchRoute(pattern, path) {
    const patternParts = pattern.split('/');
    const pathParts = path.split('/');

    if (patternParts.length !== pathParts.length) return null;

    const params = {};
    for (let i = 0; i < patternParts.length; i++) {
        if (patternParts[i].startsWith(':')) {
            params[patternParts[i].slice(1)] = pathParts[i];
        } else if (patternParts[i] !== pathParts[i]) {
            return null;
        }
    }

    return { params };
}

function navigateTo(view, routeParams, queryParams) {
    const store = Alpine.store('app');

    // Update view state
    store.currentView = view;
    store.routeParams = routeParams;

    // Handle view-specific logic
    switch (view) {
        case 'issue':
            store.selectedIssueId = routeParams.id;
            break;
        case 'issues':
            // Apply query params to filters
            if (queryParams.has('status')) {
                store.filters.status = queryParams.get('status').split(',');
            }
            if (queryParams.has('type')) {
                store.filters.type = queryParams.get('type').split(',');
            }
            if (queryParams.has('search')) {
                store.filters.search = queryParams.get('search');
            }
            break;
    }
}
```

### Navigation Helpers
```javascript
function navigate(path) {
    window.location.hash = path;
}

function navigateToIssue(id) {
    navigate(`/issue/${id}`);
}

function navigateToIssues(filters = {}) {
    const params = new URLSearchParams();
    if (filters.status?.length) params.set('status', filters.status.join(','));
    if (filters.type?.length) params.set('type', filters.type.join(','));
    if (filters.search) params.set('search', filters.search);

    const query = params.toString();
    navigate(`/issues${query ? '?' + query : ''}`);
}

function goBack() {
    window.history.back();
}
```

### Alpine.js Integration
```javascript
Alpine.store('app', {
    currentView: 'dashboard',
    routeParams: {},
    selectedIssueId: null,

    // Computed
    get currentIssue() {
        if (!this.selectedIssueId) return null;
        return this.issues.find(i => i.id === this.selectedIssueId);
    }
});
```

### View Rendering
```html
<main>
    <!-- Dashboard -->
    <div x-show="$store.app.currentView === 'dashboard'" x-cloak>
        <div x-data="dashboardView()">
            <!-- Dashboard content -->
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Issues List -->
    <div x-show="$store.app.currentView === 'issues'" x-cloak>
        <div x-data="issuesView()">
            <!-- Issues list content -->
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Issue Detail -->
    <div x-show="$store.app.currentView === 'issue'" x-cloak>
        <div x-data="issueDetailView()">
            <!-- Issue detail content -->
        </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Insights -->
    <div x-show="$store.app.currentView === 'insights'" x-cloak>
        <div x-data="insightsView()">
            <!-- Insights content -->
        </div>
    </div>
</main>
```

### Browser History
Hash-based routing automatically works with browser back/forward buttons via the `hashchange` event.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Direct URL access works (refresh preserves state)
- [ ] Browser back/forward buttons work
- [ ] Filters preserved in URL
- [ ] Issue detail links shareable
- [ ] Default route is dashboard
- [ ] Invalid routes redirect to dashboard
- [ ] No flash of wrong content on navigation

## Notes
- Hash routing chosen over History API because it works without server config
- URL remains readable and bookmarkable
- Query params allow sharing filtered views

# Visual What-If Simulation

## Context
When user clicks an open issue in the graph, animate the cascade of unblocks.

## Requirements

### 1. Click Handler for What-If
```javascript
function handleWhatIfClick(node) {
    if (node.status !== 'open') return;

    // Call WASM what-if
    const result = JSON.parse(GRAPH.what_if_close(
        NODE_MAP.get(node.id), 
        buildClosedSet()
    ));

    // Animate the unblocks
    animateUnblockCascade(node.id, result.unblocked_ids);
}
```

### 2. Cascade Animation
```javascript
function animateUnblockCascade(sourceId, unblockedIds) {
    // Phase 1: Highlight the source (pulse green)
    highlightNode(sourceId, 'closing');

    // Phase 2: Ripple out to direct unblocks (delay 200ms)
    setTimeout(() => {
        unblockedIds.forEach((id, i) => {
            setTimeout(() => {
                highlightNode(id, 'unblocked');
                // Animate the edge
                animateEdge(sourceId, id);
            }, i * 100); // Stagger for ripple effect
        });
    }, 200);

    // Phase 3: Show summary popup
    setTimeout(() => {
        showWhatIfSummary(sourceId, unblockedIds);
    }, unblockedIds.length * 100 + 500);
}
```

### 3. Visual Feedback
- Source node: pulses, shrinks, turns green
- Unblocked nodes: glow effect, color shift orangeâ†’blue
- Edges: animate with particle flow
- Summary tooltip with stats

### 4. Reset Mechanism
- 'Reset' button restores original colors
- Click elsewhere to dismiss
- Escape key to cancel

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Click open node triggers what-if
- [ ] Cascade animation is smooth and clear
- [ ] Direct unblocks highlighted distinctly
- [ ] Summary shows impact stats
- [ ] Reset works correctly

# Implement Local Preview Server with Hot Reload

## Context
Users need to preview their static site locally before deploying. This requires a simple HTTP server with some nice-to-have features like watching for changes.

## Requirements

### Basic Server
```go
// pkg/export/preview.go

type PreviewServer struct {
    bundlePath string
    port       int
    server     *http.Server
    watcher    *fsnotify.Watcher
    clients    map[chan bool]bool // SSE clients for hot reload
    mu         sync.Mutex
}

func NewPreviewServer(bundlePath string, port int) *PreviewServer {
    return &PreviewServer{
        bundlePath: bundlePath,
        port:       port,
        clients:    make(map[chan bool]bool),
    }
}

func (p *PreviewServer) Start() error {
    mux := http.NewServeMux()

    // Static file server
    fs := http.FileServer(http.Dir(p.bundlePath))
    mux.Handle("/", noCache(fs))

    // SSE endpoint for hot reload
    mux.HandleFunc("/__preview__/events", p.sseHandler)

    // Status endpoint
    mux.HandleFunc("/__preview__/status", p.statusHandler)

    p.server = &http.Server{
        Addr:    fmt.Sprintf(":%d", p.port),
        Handler: mux,
    }

    return p.server.ListenAndServe()
}
```

### No-Cache Middleware
Ensure browsers always get fresh content during preview:
```go
func noCache(next http.Handler) http.Handler {
    return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
        w.Header().Set("Cache-Control", "no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate")
        w.Header().Set("Pragma", "no-cache")
        w.Header().Set("Expires", "0")
        next.ServeHTTP(w, r)
    })
}
```

### Hot Reload via SSE
```go
func (p *PreviewServer) sseHandler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
    w.Header().Set("Content-Type", "text/event-stream")
    w.Header().Set("Cache-Control", "no-cache")
    w.Header().Set("Connection", "keep-alive")

    notify := make(chan bool)
    p.mu.Lock()
    p.clients[notify] = true
    p.mu.Unlock()

    defer func() {
        p.mu.Lock()
        delete(p.clients, notify)
        p.mu.Unlock()
    }()

    for {
        select {
        case <-notify:
            fmt.Fprintf(w, "data: reload\n\n")
            w.(http.Flusher).Flush()
        case <-r.Context().Done():
            return
        }
    }
}

func (p *PreviewServer) notifyClients() {
    p.mu.Lock()
    defer p.mu.Unlock()
    for ch := range p.clients {
        select {
        case ch <- true:
        default:
        }
    }
}
```

### File Watcher
```go
func (p *PreviewServer) StartWatcher() error {
    watcher, err := fsnotify.NewWatcher()
    if err != nil {
        return err
    }
    p.watcher = watcher

    go func() {
        for {
            select {
            case event := <-watcher.Events:
                if event.Op&(fsnotify.Write|fsnotify.Create) != 0 {
                    p.notifyClients()
                }
            case err := <-watcher.Errors:
                log.Printf("watcher error: %v", err)
            }
        }
    }()

    // Watch data directory
    return watcher.Add(filepath.Join(p.bundlePath, "data"))
}
```

### Viewer Integration
Add SSE client to viewer.js:
```javascript
// Only in preview mode (detect via /__preview__/status)
if (window.location.hostname === 'localhost' || window.location.hostname === '127.0.0.1') {
    const eventSource = new EventSource('/__preview__/events');
    eventSource.onmessage = (event) => {
        if (event.data === 'reload') {
            window.location.reload();
        }
    };
}
```

### Interactive Controls
When running preview from wizard:
```
Preview server running at http://localhost:9000

Keyboard controls:
  r - Force refresh (regenerate export)
  d - Deploy to GitHub Pages
  q - Quit preview

Press 'r' to regenerate, 'd' to deploy, or 'q' to quit...
```

### Port Selection
```go
func findAvailablePort(start, end int) (int, error) {
    for port := start; port <= end; port++ {
        listener, err := net.Listen("tcp", fmt.Sprintf(":%d", port))
        if err == nil {
            listener.Close()
            return port, nil
        }
    }
    return 0, fmt.Errorf("no available port in range %d-%d", start, end)
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Server starts and serves bundle
- [ ] No-cache headers prevent stale content
- [ ] Browser auto-opens on start
- [ ] SSE hot reload works when files change
- [ ] 'r' key regenerates export
- [ ] 'd' key triggers deployment flow
- [ ] 'q' key cleanly exits
- [ ] Auto-selects available port if default in use
- [ ] Works on macOS, Linux, Windows

## Notes
- Keep dependencies minimal (just std lib + fsnotify)
- SSE is simpler than WebSocket for this use case
- Hot reload is nice-to-have, not critical for MVP

# Add Cloudflare Pages Deployment Support via wrangler

## Context
Cloudflare Pages offers fast global CDN deployment. This task adds support for deploying via the `wrangler` CLI tool, mirroring mcp_agent_mail's approach.

## Requirements

### Advantages of Cloudflare Pages
- Faster global CDN than GitHub Pages
- Native _headers file support (no service worker needed)
- Larger file limits (25MB vs GitHub's soft limits)
- Preview deployments for branches

### wrangler CLI Operations
```go
// pkg/export/cloudflare.go

func CheckWranglerInstalled() (bool, error) {
    _, err := exec.LookPath("wrangler")
    return err == nil, nil
}

func InstallWrangler() error {
    // Check npm available
    if _, err := exec.LookPath("npm"); err != nil {
        return fmt.Errorf("npm required - install Node.js from https://nodejs.org/")
    }

    cmd := exec.Command("npm", "install", "-g", "wrangler")
    cmd.Stdout = os.Stdout
    cmd.Stderr = os.Stderr
    return cmd.Run()
}

func CheckWranglerAuthenticated() (bool, error) {
    cmd := exec.Command("wrangler", "whoami")
    return cmd.Run() == nil, nil
}

func AuthenticateWrangler() error {
    cmd := exec.Command("wrangler", "login")
    cmd.Stdin = os.Stdin
    cmd.Stdout = os.Stdout
    cmd.Stderr = os.Stderr
    return cmd.Run()
}
```

### Deployment
```go
func DeployToCloudflarePages(bundlePath string, projectName string) (string, error) {
    cmd := exec.Command("wrangler", "pages", "deploy",
        bundlePath,
        "--project-name", projectName,
        "--branch", "main",
    )

    output, err := cmd.CombinedOutput()
    if err != nil {
        return "", fmt.Errorf("deployment failed: %s", output)
    }

    // Parse URL from output
    return parseCloudflareURL(string(output)), nil
}

func parseCloudflareURL(output string) string {
    // Look for pattern: https://xxx.pages.dev
    re := regexp.MustCompile(`https://[^\s]+\.pages\.dev[^\s]*`)
    match := re.FindString(output)
    if match != "" {
        return match
    }
    return ""
}
```

### _headers File Generation
Add to bundle for COOP/COEP (not needed for our use case, but good practice):
```
/*
  X-Frame-Options: DENY
  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
  Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin
```

### Wizard Integration
Add option in deployment target selection:
```
Where do you want to deploy?
  1. GitHub Pages (create new repository)
  2. Cloudflare Pages (fast global CDN)  â† NEW
  3. Export locally only
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Detects wrangler installation
- [ ] Offers npm install if missing
- [ ] Checks and triggers authentication
- [ ] Deploys bundle to Cloudflare Pages
- [ ] Parses and returns deployment URL
- [ ] Generates _headers file in bundle
- [ ] Works in wizard flow
- [ ] Clear error messages for failures

## Notes
- Priority P3 since GitHub Pages is the primary target
- Cloudflare requires a Cloudflare account (free tier works)
- First deploy creates the project automatically

# Implement Issues List with SQL-Powered Filtering

## Context
The issues list queries the SQLite database using sql.js, enabling powerful filtering and sorting without loading all data into memory.

## Requirements

### SQL-Powered Filtering
```javascript
function buildIssueQuery(filters, sort, limit, offset) {
  let sql = `SELECT * FROM issue_overview_mv WHERE 1=1`;
  const params = [];

  // Status filter
  if (filters.status?.length) {
    sql += ` AND status IN (${filters.status.map(() => '?').join(',')})`;
    params.push(...filters.status);
  }

  // Type filter
  if (filters.type?.length) {
    sql += ` AND issue_type IN (${filters.type.map(() => '?').join(',')})`;
    params.push(...filters.type);
  }

  // Priority filter
  if (filters.priority?.length) {
    sql += ` AND priority IN (${filters.priority.map(() => '?').join(',')})`;
    params.push(...filters.priority);
  }

  // Label filter (JSON array contains)
  if (filters.labels?.length) {
    const labelClauses = filters.labels.map(() => `labels LIKE ?`);
    sql += ` AND (${labelClauses.join(' OR ')})`;
    params.push(...filters.labels.map(l => `%"${l}"%`));
  }

  // Assignee filter
  if (filters.assignee) {
    sql += ` AND assignee = ?`;
    params.push(filters.assignee);
  }

  // Blocked/blocking filter
  if (filters.hasBlockers === true) {
    sql += ` AND blocked_by_count > 0`;
  } else if (filters.hasBlockers === false) {
    sql += ` AND blocked_by_count = 0`;
  }

  // Full-text search
  if (filters.search) {
    sql += ` AND id IN (SELECT id FROM issues_fts WHERE issues_fts MATCH ?)`;
    params.push(filters.search + '*');
  }

  // Sorting
  sql += ` ORDER BY ${getSortClause(sort)}`;

  // Pagination
  sql += ` LIMIT ? OFFSET ?`;
  params.push(limit, offset);

  return { sql, params };
}

function getSortClause(sort) {
  const clauses = {
    'priority': 'priority ASC, triage_score DESC',
    'updated': 'updated_at DESC',
    'created': 'created_at DESC',
    'score': 'triage_score DESC',
    'blocks': 'blocks_count DESC',
    'title': 'title ASC'
  };
  return clauses[sort] || clauses.priority;
}
```

### FTS5 Search with Snippets
```javascript
function searchWithSnippets(term) {
  return db.exec(`
    SELECT 
      i.*,
      snippet(issues_fts, 1, '<mark>', '</mark>', '...', 32) as title_snippet,
      snippet(issues_fts, 2, '<mark>', '</mark>', '...', 64) as desc_snippet,
      bm25(issues_fts, 1.0, 5.0, 2.0, 1.0, 0.5) as relevance
    FROM issues_fts fts
    JOIN issue_overview_mv i ON fts.id = i.id
    WHERE issues_fts MATCH ?
    ORDER BY relevance
    LIMIT 100
  `, [term + '*']);
}
```

### Pagination (not virtual scroll)
```javascript
function issuesList() {
  return {
    page: 1,
    pageSize: 50,
    totalCount: 0,

    get offset() { return (this.page - 1) * this.pageSize; },
    get totalPages() { return Math.ceil(this.totalCount / this.pageSize); },

    async loadPage() {
      const { sql, params } = buildIssueQuery(
        Alpine.store('app').filters,
        Alpine.store('app').sort,
        this.pageSize,
        this.offset
      );

      const results = db.exec(sql, params);
      this.issues = results[0]?.values || [];

      // Get total count for pagination
      const countSql = sql.replace(/SELECT \*/, 'SELECT COUNT(*)').replace(/LIMIT.*/, '');
      this.totalCount = db.exec(countSql, params.slice(0, -2))[0]?.values[0][0] || 0;
    },

    nextPage() {
      if (this.page < this.totalPages) {
        this.page++;
        this.loadPage();
      }
    },

    prevPage() {
      if (this.page > 1) {
        this.page--;
        this.loadPage();
      }
    }
  };
}
```

