# Temporal Correlation

## Context
When a bead was "in progress" from T1 to T2 by author "bob@dev", commits by bob@dev between T1 and T2 are LIKELY related to that bead.

This is lower confidence (40-70%) because:
- Bob might have multiple beads in progress
- The commit might be unrelated refactoring

But it's still useful as a fallback when other methods don't apply.

## Algorithm
1. Find bead's claimed timestamp (T1) and closed timestamp (T2)
2. Find all commits by the claiming author between T1 and T2
3. Filter out commits already correlated via higher-confidence methods
4. Calculate dynamic confidence based on context

## Dynamic Confidence Calculation
\`\`\`go
func calculateTemporalConfidence(bead, commit, context) float64 {
    base := 0.50

    // Factor 1: How many beads was this author working on?
    if activeBeads == 1 {
        base += 0.20  // Only one bead = higher confidence
    } else if activeBeads > 3 {
        base -= 0.10  // Many beads = lower confidence
    }

    // Factor 2: How long is the time window?
    if window < 4*time.Hour {
        base += 0.10  // Short window = more focused
    } else if window > 7*24*time.Hour {
        base -= 0.15  // Week+ window = lots of potential commits
    }

    // Factor 3: Does commit touch files related to bead?
    if pathsMatchBeadHints(commit.Files, bead.Title) {
        base += 0.15  // File paths match keywords in title
    }

    return clamp(base, 0.20, 0.85)
}
\`\`\`

## Path Hint Extraction
Extract potential file paths from bead title/description:
- File paths: path/to/file.go
- Package names: pkg/auth, src/components
- Keywords: auth, login, user, api, db, config

## File Location
\`pkg/correlation/temporal.go\`

## Acceptance Criteria
1. Finds commits within bead's active window
2. Matches by author/email
3. Dynamic confidence based on context
4. Extracts and uses path hints
5. Never overwrites higher-confidence correlations

# Port K-Core Decomposition to Rust WASM

## Context
K-core decomposition finds the maximal subgraph where every node has degree â‰¥ k. Core number = highest k for which node is in k-core. High core = densely connected region.

## Go Implementation Reference
```go
// computeKCore in graph.go
// Iterative k-peeling on undirected view
```

## Rust Implementation (kcore.rs)
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;

/// Compute k-core numbers for all nodes.
/// Uses undirected view (edge uâ†’v treated as u--v).
pub fn kcore(graph: &DiGraph) -> Vec<u32> {
    let n = graph.node_count();
    if n == 0 {
        return Vec::new();
    }

    // Build undirected degree (in + out, deduplicated)
    let mut degree: Vec<usize> = vec![0; n];
    let mut neighbors: Vec<Vec<usize>> = vec![Vec::new(); n];

    for u in 0..n {
        for &v in graph.successors(u) {
            if !neighbors[u].contains(&v) {
                neighbors[u].push(v);
                degree[u] += 1;
            }
            if !neighbors[v].contains(&u) {
                neighbors[v].push(u);
                degree[v] += 1;
            }
        }
    }

    let max_deg = degree.iter().cloned().max().unwrap_or(0);
    let mut core = vec![0u32; n];
    let mut removed = vec![false; n];

    for k in 1..=max_deg {
        // Find nodes with degree < k
        let mut queue: Vec<usize> = (0..n)
            .filter(|&i| !removed[i] && degree[i] < k)
            .collect();

        while let Some(v) = queue.pop() {
            if removed[v] { continue; }
            removed[v] = true;
            core[v] = (k - 1) as u32;

            for &nbr in &neighbors[v] {
                if removed[nbr] { continue; }
                degree[nbr] -= 1;
                if degree[nbr] < k {
                    queue.push(nbr);
                }
            }
        }
    }

    // Remaining nodes get max_deg
    for i in 0..n {
        if !removed[i] {
            core[i] = max_deg as u32;
        }
    }

    core
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Core numbers computed correctly
- [ ] Handles isolated nodes (core 0)
- [ ] Results match Go implementation

# Port TopK Set Algorithm

## Context
TopK Set finds the k issues that, when completed, maximize the total downstream unlocks. Uses greedy submodular optimization.

## Go Implementation Reference
```go
// generateTopKSet in advanced_insights.go
// Greedy selection maximizing marginal unlocks
```

## Rust Implementation (advanced/topk_set.rs)
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;
use crate::whatif;

#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct TopKSetItem {
    pub node: usize,
    pub marginal_gain: usize,
}

pub struct TopKSetResult {
    pub items: Vec<TopKSetItem>,
    pub total_gain: usize,
}

/// Greedy submodular selection for maximum unlock.
pub fn topk_set(graph: &DiGraph, closed_set: &[bool], k: usize) -> TopKSetResult {
    let n = graph.node_count();
    let mut selected = Vec::new();
    let mut current_closed = closed_set.to_vec();
    let mut total_gain = 0;

    for _ in 0..k {
        // Find node with maximum marginal gain
        let mut best_node = None;
        let mut best_gain = 0;

        for v in 0..n {
            if current_closed[v] { continue; }

            let result = whatif::what_if_close(graph, v, &current_closed);
            if result.transitive_unblocks > best_gain {
                best_gain = result.transitive_unblocks;
                best_node = Some(v);
            }
        }

        match best_node {
            Some(node) => {
                selected.push(TopKSetItem {
                    node,
                    marginal_gain: best_gain,
                });
                current_closed[node] = true;
                total_gain += best_gain;
            }
            None => break, // No more beneficial nodes
        }
    }

    TopKSetResult {
        items: selected,
        total_gain,
    }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Greedy selection maximizes total gain
- [ ] Returns k items (or fewer if exhausted)
- [ ] Marginal gains decrease monotonically

# Port Eigenvector Centrality to Rust WASM

## Context
Eigenvector centrality measures node importance based on connections to other important nodes. Unlike PageRank, it uses the principal eigenvector of the adjacency matrix directly.

## Go Implementation Reference
```go
// computeEigenvector in graph.go
// Power iteration with 50 iterations
// Deterministic ordering for reproducibility
```

## Rust Implementation (eigenvector.rs)
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;

/// Compute eigenvector centrality using power iteration.
/// Uses incoming edges (nodes pointed TO are important).
pub fn eigenvector(graph: &DiGraph, iterations: u32) -> Vec<f64> {
    let n = graph.node_count();
    if n == 0 {
        return Vec::new();
    }

    // Initialize with uniform distribution
    let mut vec = vec![1.0 / n as f64; n];
    let mut work = vec![0.0; n];

    for _ in 0..iterations {
        // Reset work vector
        for w in &mut work {
            *w = 0.0;
        }

        // Multiply: work = A^T * vec (sum of predecessor scores)
        for v in 0..n {
            for &u in graph.predecessors(v) {
                work[v] += vec[u];
            }
        }

        // Normalize to unit length
        let norm: f64 = work.iter().map(|x| x * x).sum::<f64>().sqrt();
        if norm == 0.0 {
            break;
        }
        for w in &mut work {
            *w /= norm;
        }

        std::mem::swap(&mut vec, &mut work);
    }

    vec
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Power iteration converges
- [ ] Results match Go implementation
- [ ] Handles disconnected graphs
- [ ] Performance: <5ms for 1000 nodes

