# Port Cycle Break Suggestions

## Context
Cycle Break analyzes which edges to remove to break cycles with minimal collateral damage.

## Go Implementation Reference
```go
// generateCycleBreakSuggestions in advanced_insights.go
```

## Rust Implementation (advanced/cycle_break.rs)
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;
use crate::algorithms::cycles::tarjan_scc;

pub struct CycleBreakItem {
    pub from: usize,
    pub to: usize,
    pub cycles_broken: usize,
    pub collateral: usize,
}

/// Suggest edges to remove for breaking cycles.
pub fn cycle_break_suggestions(graph: &DiGraph, limit: usize) -> Vec<CycleBreakItem> {
    let scc = tarjan_scc(graph);
    if !scc.has_cycles {
        return Vec::new();
    }

    let mut suggestions = Vec::new();

    // For each SCC with >1 node, find edges within it
    for component in &scc.components {
        if component.len() <= 1 { continue; }

        let comp_set: std::collections::HashSet<usize> = component.iter().copied().collect();

        for &from in component {
            for &to in graph.successors(from) {
                if comp_set.contains(&to) {
                    // This edge is within a cycle
                    let collateral = graph.successors(from).len() + graph.predecessors(to).len();

                    suggestions.push(CycleBreakItem {
                        from,
                        to,
                        cycles_broken: 1, // Simplified: assume breaks 1 cycle
                        collateral,
                    });
                }
            }
        }
    }

    // Sort by collateral (ascending) - prefer minimal impact
    suggestions.sort_by(|a, b| a.collateral.cmp(&b.collateral));
    suggestions.truncate(limit);
    suggestions
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Only suggests edges within cycles
- [ ] Collateral damage computed
- [ ] Sorted by minimal impact

# WASM Memory Management

## Context
Rust WASM objects allocated via wasm-bindgen are NOT automatically garbage collected by JavaScript. Each DiGraph, subgraph, or result object must be explicitly freed to prevent memory leaks.

## Requirements

### 1. Implement .free() on all exported types
wasm-bindgen automatically generates .free() methods, but we need to:
- Document their usage
- Ensure all exported types support it
- Add defensive checks

### 2. JavaScript Patterns for Memory Safety
```javascript
// BAD: Memory leak
function analyze() {
    const subgraph = GRAPH.subgraph(indices);
    return subgraph.pagerank(0.85, 100);
    // subgraph never freed!
}

// GOOD: Explicit cleanup
function analyze() {
    const subgraph = GRAPH.subgraph(indices);
    try {
        return subgraph.pagerank(0.85, 100);
    } finally {
        subgraph.free();
    }
}

// BETTER: Helper wrapper
function withSubgraph(indices, fn) {
    const subgraph = GRAPH.subgraph(indices);
    try {
        return fn(subgraph);
    } finally {
        subgraph.free();
    }
}
```

### 3. Alpine.js Store Cleanup
```javascript
Alpine.store('graph', {
    instance: null,
    destroy() {
        if (this.instance) {
            this.instance.free();
            this.instance = null;
        }
    }
});

// Call on page unload
window.addEventListener('beforeunload', () => {
    Alpine.store('graph').destroy();
});
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] All DiGraph methods documented re: memory
- [ ] Helper functions for safe subgraph usage
- [ ] Cleanup on page unload
- [ ] No memory leaks in 10-minute usage session

