# Port Topological Sort to Rust WASM

## Context
Topological sort orders nodes such that for every edge uâ†’v, u comes before v. Essential for execution planning and critical path analysis.

## Rust Implementation (topo.rs)
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;
use std::collections::VecDeque;

/// Topological sort using Kahn's algorithm.
/// Returns None if graph has cycles.
pub fn topological_sort(graph: &DiGraph) -> Option<Vec<usize>> {
    let n = graph.node_count();
    if n == 0 {
        return Some(Vec::new());
    }

    // Compute in-degrees
    let mut in_degree: Vec<usize> = graph.in_degrees();

    // Queue of nodes with no incoming edges
    let mut queue: VecDeque<usize> = (0..n)
        .filter(|&i| in_degree[i] == 0)
        .collect();

    let mut order = Vec::with_capacity(n);

    while let Some(u) = queue.pop_front() {
        order.push(u);

        for &v in graph.successors(u) {
            in_degree[v] -= 1;
            if in_degree[v] == 0 {
                queue.push_back(v);
            }
        }
    }

    if order.len() == n {
        Some(order)
    } else {
        None // Cycle detected
    }
}

/// Check if graph is a DAG (has valid topological order).
pub fn is_dag(graph: &DiGraph) -> bool {
    topological_sort(graph).is_some()
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Returns valid topological order for DAGs
- [ ] Returns None for cyclic graphs
- [ ] Deterministic output order
- [ ] Performance: <2ms for 1000 nodes

# Port HITS Algorithm to Rust WASM

## Context
HITS (Hyperlink-Induced Topic Search) computes hub and authority scores. Hubs point to many authorities; authorities are pointed to by many hubs.

## Go Implementation Reference
```go
// network.HITS(a.g, 1e-3) from gonum
```

## Rust Implementation (hits.rs)
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;

pub struct HITSResult {
    pub hubs: Vec<f64>,
    pub authorities: Vec<f64>,
}

/// Compute HITS hub and authority scores.
pub fn hits(graph: &DiGraph, tolerance: f64, max_iterations: u32) -> HITSResult {
    let n = graph.node_count();
    if n == 0 {
        return HITSResult { hubs: Vec::new(), authorities: Vec::new() };
    }

    let mut hubs = vec![1.0; n];
    let mut auth = vec![1.0; n];

    for _ in 0..max_iterations {
        let mut new_auth = vec![0.0; n];
        let mut new_hubs = vec![0.0; n];

        // Authority score = sum of hub scores of predecessors
        for v in 0..n {
            for &u in graph.predecessors(v) {
                new_auth[v] += hubs[u];
            }
        }

        // Hub score = sum of authority scores of successors
        for u in 0..n {
            for &v in graph.successors(u) {
                new_hubs[u] += new_auth[v];
            }
        }

        // Normalize
        let auth_norm = normalize(&mut new_auth);
        let hubs_norm = normalize(&mut new_hubs);

        // Check convergence
        let diff: f64 = hubs.iter().zip(new_hubs.iter())
            .map(|(a, b)| (a - b).abs())
            .sum::<f64>()
            + auth.iter().zip(new_auth.iter())
            .map(|(a, b)| (a - b).abs())
            .sum();

        hubs = new_hubs;
        auth = new_auth;

        if diff < tolerance {
            break;
        }
    }

    HITSResult { hubs, authorities: auth }
}

fn normalize(vec: &mut [f64]) -> f64 {
    let sum: f64 = vec.iter().sum();
    if sum > 0.0 {
        for v in vec.iter_mut() {
            *v /= sum;
        }
    }
    sum
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Hub and authority scores converge
- [ ] Results match Go gonum implementation
- [ ] Returns JSON: {hubs: [], authorities: []}

# Implement Subgraph Extraction

## Context
Subgraph extraction creates a new graph containing only specified nodes and their interconnections. Essential for filtered-view analysis.

## Rust Implementation (subgraph.rs)
```rust
use crate::graph::DiGraph;

impl DiGraph {
    /// Extract subgraph containing only the specified node indices.
    /// Returns new DiGraph with edges between retained nodes.
    pub fn subgraph(&self, node_indices: &[usize]) -> DiGraph {
        // Create mapping: old index -> new index
        let mut index_map: Vec<Option<usize>> = vec![None; self.node_count()];
        let mut new_graph = DiGraph::with_capacity(node_indices.len(), node_indices.len() * 2);

        // Add nodes
        for (new_idx, &old_idx) in node_indices.iter().enumerate() {
            if old_idx < self.nodes.len() {
                new_graph.add_node(&self.nodes[old_idx]);
                index_map[old_idx] = Some(new_idx);
            }
        }

        // Add edges between retained nodes
        for &old_from in node_indices {
            if let Some(new_from) = index_map.get(old_from).copied().flatten() {
                for &old_to in self.successors(old_from) {
                    if let Some(new_to) = index_map.get(old_to).copied().flatten() {
                        new_graph.add_edge(new_from, new_to);
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        new_graph
    }

    /// Create subgraph from node IDs (string lookup).
    pub fn subgraph_by_ids(&self, ids: &[&str]) -> DiGraph {
        let indices: Vec<usize> = ids.iter()
            .filter_map(|id| self.node_idx(id))
            .collect();
        self.subgraph(&indices)
    }
}
```

### WASM Binding
